[The newly confirmed cases of WPV1 associated paralytic disease in Pakistan were reported earlier (see Poliomyelitis update (70): Pakistan (KP, SD) 20190826.6641139). While there have been no newly confirmed cases reported from Afghanistan this week nor have there been positive environmental samples reported from either Pakistan or Afghanistan, it doesn't mean the virus is not still circulating, just that there aren't new confirmations. This year (2019) is clearly a major year for WPV activity in the remaining endemic areas, Pakistan and Afghanistan.

As for cVDPVs, the number of cases continues to grow with 6 newly confirmed cases, all coming from the DR Congo. That being said, there is now a positive environmental sample in the capital city area of Ghana (previously it was identified in the Northern Province), and Nigeria. Again, the absence of newly confirmed cases in countries that have recently reported activity (either AFP associated cVDPVs or positive environmental samples, or positive samples from asymptomatic individuals) should not categorically be interpreted as interrupted transmission of the cVDPVs.

As done in previous posts, to visualize all of this activity, I am putting links to HealthMap/ProMED-mail maps of countries with poliovirus activity during the past 12 months below. The size of the list remains impressive, now with 19 countries: 12 in Africa, 5 in Asia, and 2 in the Western Pacific.

